[m
[1mNAME[0m[m
       date - print or set the system date and time[m
[m
[1mSYNOPSIS[0m[m
       [1mdate[0m [[4mOPTION[24m]... [[4m+FORMAT[24m][m
       [1mdate[0m [[4m-u|--utc|--universal[24m] [[4mMMDDhhmm[24m[[[4mCC[24m][4mYY[24m][[4m.ss[24m]][m
[m
[1mDESCRIPTION[0m[m
       Display the current time in the given FORMAT, or set the system date.[m
[m
       Mandatory  arguments  to  long  options are mandatory for short options[m
       too.[m
[m
       [1m-d[0m, [1m--date[0m=[4mSTRING[24m[m
              display time described by STRING, not 'now'[m
[m
       [1m-f[0m, [1m--file[0m=[4mDATEFILE[24m[m
              like [1m--date[0m; once for each line of DATEFILE[m
[m
       [1m-I[FMT][0m, [1m--iso-8601[0m[=[4mFMT[24m][m
              output date/time in ISO 8601 format.  FMT='date' for  date  only[m
[7m Manual page date(1) line 1 (press h for help or q to quit)[27m[K[K[?1l>[?1049l]0;hrolfur@hrolfur-Lenovo-Yoga-2-13: ~[01;32mhrolfur@hrolfur-Lenovo-Yoga-2-13[00m:[01;34m~[00m$

[21;1H  R                    Repaint screen, discarding buffered input.[m
[22;1H        ---------------------------------------------------[m
[23;1H        Default "window" is the screen height.[m
[24;1H        Default "half-window" is half of the screen height.[m
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------[m
[m
                          [1mSEARCHING[0m[m
[m
  /[4mpattern[24m          *  Search forward for ([4mN[24m-th) matching line.[m
  ?[4mpattern[24m          *  Search backward for ([4mN[24m-th) matching line.[m
  n                 *  Repeat previous search (for [4mN[24m-th occurrence).[m
  N                 *  Repeat previous search in reverse direction.[m
  ESC-n             *  Repeat previous search, spanning [7mfile[27ms.[m
  ESC-N             *  Repeat previous search, reverse dir. & spanning [7mfile[27ms.[m
  ESC-u                Undo (toggle) search highlighting.[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K  &[4mpattern[24m          *  Display only matching lines[m
        ---------------------------------------------------[m
        A search pattern may be preceded by one or more of:[m
        ^N or !  Search for NON-matching lines.[m
        ^E or *  Search multiple [7mfile[27ms (pass thru END OF [7mFILE[27m).[m
        ^F or @  Start search at FIRST [7mfile[27m (for /) or last [7mfile[27m (for ?).[m
        ^K       Highlight matches, but don't move (KEEP position).[m
        ^R       Don't use REGULAR EXPRESSIONS.[m
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------[m
[m
                           [1mJUMPING[0m[m
[m
  g  <  ESC-<       *  Go to first line in [7mfile[27m (or line [4mN[24m).[m
  G  >  ESC->       *  Go to last line in [7mfile[27m (or line [4mN[24m).[m
  p  %              *  Go to beginning of [7mfile[27m (or [4mN[24m percent into [7mfile[27m).[m
  t                 *  Go to the ([4mN[24m-th) next tag.[m
  T                 *  Go to the ([4mN[24m-th) previous tag.[m
  {  (  [           *  Find close bracket } ) ].[m
  }  )  ]           *  Find open bracket { ( [.[m
  ESC-^F [4m<c1>[24m [4m<c2>[24m  *  Find close bracket [4m<c2>[24m.[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K  ESC-^B [4m<c1>[24m [4m<c2>[24m  *  Find open bracket [4m<c1>[24m [m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K        ---------------------------------------------------[m
        Each "find close bracket" command goes forward to the close bracket [m
          matching the ([4mN[24m-th) open bracket in the top line.[m
        Each "find open bracket" command goes backward to the open bracket [m
          matching the ([4mN[24m-th) close bracket in the bottom line.[m
[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K  m[4m<letter>[24m            Mark the current position with <letter>.[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K  '[4m<letter>[24m            Go to a previously marked position.[m
  ''                   Go to the previous position.[m
  ^X^X                 Same as '.[m
        ---------------------------------------------------[m
        A mark is any upper-case or lower-case letter.[m
        Certain marks are predefined:[m
             ^  means  beginning of the [7mfile[27m[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K             $  means  end of the [7mfile[27m[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K ---------------------------------------------------------------------------[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K[m
                        [1mCHANGING[0m [1m[7mFILE[27m[0m[1mS[0m[m
[m
  :e [[4m[7mfile[27m[24m]            Examine a new [7mfile[27m.[m
  ^X^V                 Same as :e.[m
  :n                *  Examine the ([4mN[24m-th) next [7mfile[27m from the command line.[m
  :p                *  Examine the ([4mN[24m-th) previous [7mfile[27m from the command line.[m
  :x                *  Examine the first (or [4mN[24m-th) [7mfile[27m from the command line.[m
  :d                   Delete the current [7mfile[27m from the command line list.[m
  =  ^G  :f            Print current [7mfile[27m name.[m
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------[m
[m
                    [1mMISCELLANEOUS[0m [1mCOMMANDS[0m[m
[m
  -[4m<flag>[24m              Toggle a command line option [see OPTIONS below].[m
  --[4m<name>[24m             Toggle a command line option, by name.[m
  _[4m<flag>[24m              Display the setting of a command line option.[m
  __[4m<name>[24m             Display the setting of an option, by name.[m
  +[4mcmd[24m                 Execute the less cmd each time a new [7mfile[27m is examined.[m
[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K  ![4mcommand[24m             Execute the shell command with $SHELL.[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K  |[1mX[0m[4mcommand[24m            Pipe [7mfile[27m between current pos & mark [1mX[0m to shell command.[m
  v                    Edit the current [7mfile[27m with $VISUAL or $EDITOR.[m
  V                    Print version number of "less".[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K ---------------------------------------------------------------------------[m
[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K                           [1mOPTIONS[0m[m
[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K        Most options may be changed either on the command line,[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K        or from within less by using the - or -- command.[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K        Options may be given in one of two forms: either a single[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K        character preceded by a -, or a name preceded by --.[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K[m
  -?  ........  --help[m
                  Display help (from command line).[m
  -a  ........  --search-skip-screen[m
                  Search skips current screen.[m
  -A  ........  --SEARCH-SKIP-SCREEN[m
                  Search starts just after target line.[m
  -b [[4mN[24m]  ....  --buffers=[[4mN[24m][m
                  Number of buffers.[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K  -B  ........  --auto-buffers[m
                  Don't automatically allocate buffers for pipes.[m
  -c  ........  --clear-screen[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K                  Repaint by clearing rather than scrolling.[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K...skipping...
                  Quit at end of [7mfile[27m.[m
  -f  ........  --force[m
                  Force open non-regular [7mfile[27ms.[m
  -F  ........  --quit-if-one-screen[m
                  Quit if entire [7mfile[27m fits on first screen.[m
  -g  ........  --hilite-search[m
                  Highlight only last match for searches.[m
  -G  ........  --HILITE-SEARCH[m
                  Don't highlight any matches for searches.[m
  -h [[4mN[24m]  ....  --max-back-scroll=[[4mN[24m][m
                  Backward scroll limit.[m
  -i  ........  --ignore-case[m
                  Ignore case in searches that do not contain uppercase.[m
  -I  ........  --IGNORE-CASE[m
                  Ignore case in all searches.[m
  -j [[4mN[24m]  ....  --jump-target=[[4mN[24m][m
                  Screen position of target lines.[m
  -J  ........  --status-column[m
                  Display a status column at left edge of screen.[m
  -k [[4m[7mfile[27m[24m]  .  --lesskey-[7mfile[27m=[[4m[7mfile[27m[24m][m
                  Use a lesskey [7mfile[27m.[m
  -K            --quit-on-intr[m
                  Exit less in response to ctrl-C.[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K  -L  ........  --no-lessopen[m
                  Ignore the LESSOPEN environment variable.[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K  -m  -M  ....  --long-prompt  --LONG-PROMPT[m
                  Set prompt style.[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K  -n  -N  ....  --line-numbers  --LINE-NUMBERS[m
                  Don't use line numbers.[m
  -o [[4m[7mfile[27m[24m]  .  --log-[7mfile[27m=[[4m[7mfile[27m[24m][m
                  Copy to log [7mfile[27m (standard input only).[m
  -O [[4m[7mfile[27m[24m]  .  --LOG-[7mFILE[27m=[[4m[7mfile[27m[24m][m
                  Copy to log [7mfile[27m (unconditionally overwrite).[m
  -p [[4mpattern[24m]  --pattern=[[4mpattern[24m][m
                  Start at pattern (from command line).[m
  -P [[4mprompt[24m]   --prompt=[[4mprompt[24m][m
                  Define new prompt.[m
  -q  -Q  ....  --quiet  --QUIET  --silent --SILENT[m
                  Quiet the terminal bell.[m
  -r  -R  ....  --raw-control-chars  --RAW-CONTROL-CHARS[m
                  Output "raw" control characters.[m
  -s  ........  --squeeze-blank-lines[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K                  Squeeze multiple blank lines.[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K  -S  ........  --chop-long-lines[m
                  Chop (truncate) long lines rather than wrapping.[m
  -t [[4mtag[24m]  ..  --tag=[[4mtag[24m][m
                  Find a tag.[m
  -T [[4mtags[24m[4m[7mfile[27m[24m] --tag-[7mfile[27m=[[4mtags[24m[4m[7mfile[27m[24m][m
                  Use an alternate tags [7mfile[27m.[m
  -u  -U  ....  --underline-special  --UNDERLINE-SPECIAL[m
                  Change handling of backspaces.[m
  -V  ........  --version[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K                  Display the version number of "less".[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K  -w  ........  --hilite-unread[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K                  Highlight first new line after forward-screen.[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K  -W  ........  --HILITE-UNREAD[m
                  Highlight first new line after any forward movement.[m
  -x [[4mN[24m[,...]]  --tabs=[[4mN[24m[,...]][m
                  Set tab stops.[m
  -X  ........  --no-init[m
                  Don't use termcap init/deinit strings.[m
  -y [[4mN[24m]  ....  --max-forw-scroll=[[4mN[24m][m
                  Forward scroll limit.[m
  -z [[4mN[24m]  ....  --window=[[4mN[24m][m
                  Set size of window.[m
  -" [[4mc[24m[[4mc[24m]]  .  --quotes=[[4mc[24m[[4mc[24m]][m
                  Set shell quote characters.[m
  -~  ........  --tilde[m
                  Don't display tildes after end of [7mfile[27m.[m
  -# [[4mN[24m]  ....  --shift=[[4mN[24m][m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K                  Horizontal scroll amount (0 = one half screen width)[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K      ........  --no-keypad[m
                  Don't send termcap keypad init/deinit strings.[m
      ........  --follow-name[m
                  The F command changes [7mfile[27ms if the input [7mfile[27m is renamed.[m
      ........  --use-backslash[m
                  Subsequent options use backslash as escape char.[m

                          [1mLINE[0m [1mEDITING[0m[m
[m
        These keys can be used to edit text being entered [m
        on the "command line" at the bottom of the screen.[m
[m
 RightArrow ..................... ESC-l ... Move cursor right one character.[m
 LeftArrow ...................... ESC-h ... Move cursor left one character.[m
 ctrl-RightArrow  ESC-RightArrow  ESC-w ... Move cursor right one word.[m
 ctrl-LeftArrow   ESC-LeftArrow   ESC-b ... Move cursor left one word.[m
 HOME ........................... ESC-0 ... Move cursor to start of line.[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K END ............................ ESC-$ ... Move cursor to end of line.[m
 BACKSPACE ................................ Delete char to left of cursor.[m
 DELETE ......................... ESC-x ... Delete char under cursor.[m
 ctrl-BACKSPACE   ESC-BACKSPACE ........... Delete word to left of cursor.[m
 ctrl-DELETE .... ESC-DELETE .... ESC-X ... Delete word under cursor.[m
 ctrl-U ......... ESC (MS-DOS only) ....... Delete entire line.[m
[7mHELP -- Press RETURN for more, or q when done[27m[K[K/[K...skipping...
 TAB ...................................... Complete [7mfile[27mname & cycle.[m
 SHIFT-TAB ...................... ESC-TAB   Complete [7mfile[27mname & reverse cycle.[m
 ctrl-L ................................... Complete [7mfile[27mname, list all.[m

DATE(1)                          User Commands                         DATE(1)[m

[1mNAME[0m[m
       date - print or set the system date and time[m
[m
[1mSYNOPSIS[0m[m
       [1mdate[0m [[4mOPTION[24m]... [[4m+FORMAT[24m][m
       [1mdate[0m [[4m-u|--utc|--universal[24m] [[4mMMDDhhmm[24m[[[4mCC[24m][4mYY[24m][[4m.ss[24m]][m
[m
[1mDESCRIPTION[0m[m
       Display the current time in the given FORMAT, or set the system date.[m
[m
       Mandatory  arguments  to  long  options are mandatory for short options[m
       too.[m
[m
       [1m-d[0m, [1m--date[0m=[4mSTRING[24m[m
              display time described by STRING, not 'now'[m
[m
       [1m-f[0m, [1m--[0m[1m[7mfile[27m[0m=[4mDATE[24m[4m[7mFILE[27m[24m[m
              like [1m--date[0m; once for each line of DATE[7mFILE[27m[m
[m
       [1m-I[FMT][0m, [1m--iso-8601[0m[=[4mFMT[24m][m
              output date/time in ISO 8601 format.  FMT='date' for  date  only[m
[7m Manual page date(1) line 1/201 14% (press h for help or q to quit)[27m[K[K[?1l>[?1049l]0;hrolfur@hrolfur-Lenovo-Yoga-2-13: ~[01;32mhrolfur@hrolfur-Lenovo-Yoga-2-13[00m:[01;34m~[00m$ man -k password

]0;hrolfur@hrolfur-Lenovo-Yoga-2-13: ~[01;32mhrolfur@hrolfur-Lenovo-Yoga-2-13[00m:[01;34m~[00m$ man5pa[K[K[K 5 passwd
[?1049h[?1h=PASSWD(5)                File Formats and Conversions                PASSWD(5)[m
[m
[1mNAME[0m[m
       passwd - the password file[m
[m
[1mDESCRIPTION[0m[m
       /etc/passwd contains one line for each user account, with seven fields[m
       delimited by colons (‚Äú:‚Äù). These fields are:[m
[m
       ¬∑   login name[m
[m
       ¬∑   optional encrypted password[m
[m
       ¬∑   numerical user ID[m
[m
       ¬∑   numerical group ID[m
[m
       ¬∑   user name or comment field[m
[m
       ¬∑   user home directory[m
[m
       ¬∑   optional user command interpreter[m
[m
[7m Manual page passwd(5) line 1 (press h for help or q to quit)[27m[K[K[?1l>[?1049l]0;hrolfur@hrolfur-Lenovo-Yoga-2-13: ~[01;32mhrolfur@hrolfur-Lenovo-Yoga-2-13[00m:[01;34m~[00m$ what [Kis passwd
passwd (1)           - change user password
passwd (1ssl)        - compute password hashes
passwd (5)           - the password file

[?1h=[?1049h[H[2J[24;1HWelcome to Info version 6.1.  Type H for help, h for tutorial.[24;1Hgzip -d < /usr/share/info/coreutils.info.gz...[K[24;1HWelcome to Info version 6.1. This is a good[K[16;6Hchoice for a date format, as it is standard and is easy to sort in[17;1H     the usual case where years are in the range 0000...9999.[18;1H‚Äò%g‚Äô[K[19;6Hyear corresponding to the ISO week number, but without the century[20;6H(range ‚Äò00‚Äô through ‚Äò99‚Äô). Seconds since the epoch are not padded, though, since there is[10;1Hno natural width for them.[11;1H[K[12;4HAs a GNU extension, ‚Äòdate‚Äô recognizes any of the following optional[13;1Hflags after the ‚Äò%‚Äô:[14;1H[K[15;1H‚Äò-‚Äô[16;1H     (hyphen) Do not pad the field; useful if the output is intended for[17;1H     human consumption.[18;1H‚Äò_‚Äô[19;1H     (underscore) Pad with spaces; useful if you need a fixed number of[20;1H     characters in the output, but zeros are too distracting.[21;1H‚Äò0‚Äô[22;1H     (zero) Pad with zeros even if the conversion specifier would[23;1H[7m-----Info: (coreutils.info.gz)Padding and other flags, 60 lines --Top-----------[0m[1;80H\[1;1H[1;1H[1;7HOptions for date,  Prev: Padding and other flags,  Up: date invocation[K[2;1H[K[3;1H21.1.5 Setting the time[4;1H-----------------------[K[5;1H[K[6;1HIf given an argument that does not start with ‚Äò+‚Äô, ‚Äòdate‚Äô sets the[7;1Hsystem clock to the date and time specified by that argument (as[K[8;1Hdescribed below).  You must have appropriate privileges to set the[K[9;1Hsystem clock.  Note for changes to persist across a reboot, the hardware[10;1Hclock may need to be updated from the system clock, which might not[11;1Hhappen automatically on your system.[12;1H[K[13;1H   The argument must consist entirely of digits, which have the[14;1Hfollowing meaning:[15;1H[K[16;1H‚ÄòMM‚Äô[K[17;6Hmonth[K[18;2HDD‚Äô[19;6Hday within month[K[20;1H‚Äòhh‚Äô[K[21;1H     hour[22;1H‚Äòmm‚Äô[K[23;1H[7m-----Info: (coreutils.info.gz)Setting the time, 36 lines --Top------------------[0m[1;1H[1;1H[1;7HExamples of date,  Prev: Setting the time,  Up: date invocation[K[3;6H6 Options for ‚Äòdate‚Äô[4;24H--[6;1HThe program accepts the following options. DATESTR can be in almost any common format.[13;4H  It can contain month names, time zones, ‚Äòam‚Äô and ‚Äòpm‚Äô, ‚Äòyesterday‚Äô,[14;1H     etc.  For example, ‚Äò--date="2004-02-27 14:19:13.489392193 +0530"‚Äô[15;1H     specifies the instant of time that is 489,392,193 nanoseconds after[16;1H     February 27, 2004 at 2:19:13 PM in a time zone that is 5 hours and[17;6H30 minutes east of UTC.[18;1H     Note: input currently must be in locale independent format. If the natural size of the output of[3;1Hthe field has less than the specified number of characters, the result[4;1His written right adjusted and padded to the given size. The modifiers are:[9;1H[K[10;2HE‚Äô[K[11;6HUse the locale‚Äôs alternate representation for date and time.  This[12;1H     modifier applies to the ‚Äò%c‚Äô, ‚Äò%C‚Äô, ‚Äò%x‚Äô, ‚Äò%X‚Äô, ‚Äò%y‚Äô and ‚Äò%Y‚Äô[13;6Hconversion specifiers. If the week containing[5;1H     January 1 has four or more days in the new year, then it is[6;1H     considered week 1; otherwise, it is week 53 of the previous year,[7;1H     and the next week is week 1.  (See the ISO 8601 standard.)[8;1H‚Äò%w‚Äô[9;1H     day of week (‚Äò0‚Äô...‚Äò6‚Äô) with 0 corresponding to Sunday[10;1H‚Äò%W‚Äô[K[11;1H     week number of year, with Monday as first day of week[12;6H(‚Äò00‚Äô...‚Äò53‚Äô). If this[8;1Hinformation is not accessible, then print the number of processors[9;1Hinstalled.  If the ‚ÄòOMP_NUM_THREADS‚Äô environment variable is set, then[10;1Hit will determine the returned value.  The result is guaranteed to be[11;1H[K[11;1Hgreater than zero.  Synopsis:[13;4H  nproc [OPTION][K[14;1H[K[15;1H   The program accepts the following options.  Also see *note Common[K[16;1Hoptions::.[K[17;1H[K[18;1H‚Äò--all‚Äô[19;1H     Print the number of installed processors on the system, which may[20;1H     be greater than the number online or available to the current[21;1H     process.  The ‚ÄòOMP_NUM_THREADS‚Äô environment variable is not honored[22;1H     in this case.[23;1H[7m-----Info: (coreutils.info.gz)nproc invocation, 29 lines --Top------------------[0m[15;57H[15;57H[24;1H[K[?1l>[?1049l[24;1H[K[?1l>[?1049l]0;hrolfur@hrolfur-Lenovo-Yoga-2-13: ~[01;32mhrolfur@hrolfur-Lenovo-Yoga-2-13[00m:[01;34m~[00m$ date --help
Usage: date [OPTION]... [+FORMAT]
  or:  date [-u|--utc|--universal] [MMDDhhmm[[CC]YY][.ss]]
Display the current time in the given FORMAT, or set the system date.

Mandatory arguments to long options are mandatory for short options too.
  -d, --date=STRING          display time described by STRING, not 'now'
  -f, --file=DATEFILE        like --date; once for each line of DATEFILE
  -I[FMT], --iso-8601[=FMT]  output date/time in ISO 8601 format.
                               FMT='date' for date only (the default),
                               'hours', 'minutes', 'seconds', or 'ns'
                               for date and time to the indicated precision.
                               Example: 2006-08-14T02:34:56-0600
  -R, --rfc-2822             output date and time in RFC 2822 format.
                               Example: Mon, 14 Aug 2006 02:34:56 -0600
      --rfc-3339=FMT         output date/time in RFC 3339 format.
                               FMT='date', 'seconds', or 'ns'
                               for date and time to the indicated precision.
                               Example: 2006-08-14 02:34:56-06:00
  -r, --reference=FILE       display the last modification time of FILE
  -s, --set=STRING           set time described by STRING
  -u, --utc, --universal     print or set Coordinated Universal Time (UTC)
      --help     display this help and exit
      --version  output version information and exit

FORMAT controls the output.  Interpreted sequences are:

  %%   a literal %
  %a   locale's abbreviated weekday name (e.g., Sun)
  %A   locale's full weekday name (e.g., Sunday)
  %b   locale's abbreviated month name (e.g., Jan)
  %B   locale's full month name (e.g., January)
  %c   locale's date and time (e.g., Thu Mar  3 23:05:25 2005)
  %C   century; like %Y, except omit last two digits (e.g., 20)
  %d   day of month (e.g., 01)
  %D   date; same as %m/%d/%y
  %e   day of month, space padded; same as %_d
  %F   full date; same as %Y-%m-%d
  %g   last two digits of year of ISO week number (see %G)
  %G   year of ISO week number (see %V); normally useful only with %V
  %h   same as %b
  %H   hour (00..23)
  %I   hour (01..12)
  %j   day of year (001..366)
  %k   hour, space padded ( 0..23); same as %_H
  %l   hour, space padded ( 1..12); same as %_I
  %m   month (01..12)
  %M   minute (00..59)
  %n   a newline
  %N   nanoseconds (000000000..999999999)
  %p   locale's equivalent of either AM or PM; blank if not known
  %P   like %p, but lower case
  %r   locale's 12-hour clock time (e.g., 11:11:04 PM)
  %R   24-hour hour and minute; same as %H:%M
  %s   seconds since 1970-01-01 00:00:00 UTC
  %S   second (00..60)
  %t   a tab
  %T   time; same as %H:%M:%S
  %u   day of week (1..7); 1 is Monday
  %U   week number of year, with Sunday as first day of week (00..53)
  %V   ISO week number, with Monday as first day of week (01..53)
  %w   day of week (0..6); 0 is Sunday
  %W   week number of year, with Monday as first day of week (00..53)
  %x   locale's date representation (e.g., 12/31/99)
  %X   locale's time representation (e.g., 23:13:48)
  %y   last two digits of year (00..99)
  %Y   year
  %z   +hhmm numeric time zone (e.g., -0400)
  %:z  +hh:mm numeric time zone (e.g., -04:00)
  %::z  +hh:mm:ss numeric time zone (e.g., -04:00:00)
  %:::z  numeric time zone with : to necessary precision (e.g., -04, +05:30)
  %Z   alphabetic time zone abbreviation (e.g., EDT)

By default, date pads numeric fields with zeroes.
The following optional flags may follow '%':

  -  (hyphen) do not pad the field
  _  (underscore) pad with spaces
  0  (zero) pad with zeros
  ^  use upper case if possible
  #  use opposite case if possible

After any flags comes an optional field width, as a decimal number;
then an optional modifier, which is either
E to use the locale's alternate representations if available, or
O to use the locale's alternate numeric symbols if available.

Examples:
Convert seconds since the epoch (1970-01-01 UTC) to a date
  $ date --date='@2147483647'

Show the time on the west coast of the US (use tzselect(1) to find TZ)
  $ TZ='America/Los_Angeles' date

Show the local time for 9AM next Friday on the west coast of the US
  $ date --date='TZ="America/Los_Angeles" 09:00 next Fri'

GNU coreutils online help: <http://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/>
Report date translation bugs to <http://translationproject.org/team/>
Full documentation at: <http://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/date>
or available locally via: info '(coreutils) date invocation'
